The Familiar in the New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism, even before these threats become generally visible?
Because they know that supposedly "harmless" hints can develop into accusations and ultimately lead to discrimination that is then codified in law.
At this point, hysteria then sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what's at stake in the game.
In this way, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it has been clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other unrefined right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often foot soldiers of fascism or communism without joining parties with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we deal with people—the "educated middle class" associated with mass media, politics, government, and universities—who condemn Israel in language that often recalls that of the riders on the backs of these antidemocratic movements.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world — not yet, fortunately — but it is the voice of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom should be mentioned: recently, during a dinner party in London, he referred to Israel as "this fucking little country."
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
What is alarming, however, are the reactions to it.
He was neither recalled by his government nor did the government call for his recall. In public, the matter was treated as just another scandal to be put aside.
The French press portrayed the ambassador as a genuine victim of British bullying, not of his own contemptible attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador in Britain has several allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard, however, did us a service: through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish sentiments are.
As a columnist put it so aptly: Israel has become the object of hatred, whose name one dares not utter.
But we are not only daring to do so; we are even obligated to say it.
In view of the daily attacks on Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Anti-Semitic incidents are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the fact that the denial of the Holocaust has become commonplace. Nor must we remain silent about the comparisons drawn by antisemites and anti-Zionists between Israel and the Third Reich.
While Israeli soldiers are portrayed in a Palestinian TV program as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "fight against the new Nazi plague that is arising in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. One hates them almost everywhere."
During the televised broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "have no mercy for the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in connection with antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Jewish hatred is not curbed, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as well as non-Jews.
Currently, the points of attack in this struggle are less clear than ever before, because a surprising aspect of today's anti-Semitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism has always remained the same—namely, to attack Jews—it nevertheless changes its face, its strategy, its justifications, and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the goal.
When these did not yield, the Jews were expelled or killed.
When in the 19th century the theory of race captivated people, Jews were attacked because of their membership in a evil race.
With the existence of the state of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today slandered as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is entirely legitimate to critically oppose certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
Antizionism is becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Antizionisten sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I'm only against the existence of Britain, but I'm not anti-British!"
Or if someone were to claim: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
One would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but to hate their state.
And yet, in connection with Israel, there are people who claim to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, Israel-bashing is routine.
This demonization of the only democratic state system in the Near East is a core element of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all good and the source of all evil," then the "doctrine of contempt" is circulating within the UN, as expressed by Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of Canada's Parliament.
This constant portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in fact a campaign against the Jewish people.
Thus, the numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries are based on demonizations of Israel that employ anti-Semitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this defamatory language in connection with the Middle East.
Compared to earlier anti-Jewish outbursts, today's antisemitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, but rather an attack on the "collective Jew," that is, on the state of Israel.
Such attacks, however, have set off a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions throughout Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous antisemites were those who wanted to make the world Judenrein.
The most dangerous antisemites today are those who want to make the world free of Jewish states.
